Stress and Lifestyle Factors Analysis¶

This project analyzes the correlations between stress levels and various lifestyle factors using a dataset titled "Sleep_health_and_lifestyle_dataset.csv."

Project Overview¶

The primary goal of this project is to explore how different lifestyle factors, such as sleep duration, quality of sleep, exercise levels, heart rate, and daily steps correlate with stress levels.

Results¶

The final output of the analysis includes:

  • Visualizations that illustrate the distribution and relationships between different lifestyle factors and stress levels.
  • A correlation matrix that quantifies how strongly each factor is correlated with stress levels.
  • A summary that highlights which lifestyle factors are most strongly associated with stress levels, offering insights into how lifestyle choices might impact stress.

Acknowledgments¶

The dataset used in this project was sourced from kaggle.com. Inspiration for this project came from the intersection of data analysis and mental health.

columns_of_interest = ['Age', 'Sleep Duration', 'Quality of Sleep', 'Physical Activity Level', 'Stress Level', 'Heart Rate', 'Daily Steps']

print(correlation_matrix)

stress_correlation = correlation_matrix['Stress Level'].drop('Stress Level')
print("\nCorrelation of Stress Level with other variables:")
print(stress_correlation)

plt.title('Correlation of Stress Level with Various Variables')
plt.xlabel('Variables')
plt.ylabel('Correlation Coefficient')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1000x600 with 0 Axes>

Age and Stress Level (-0.422344):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a moderate negative correlation between Age and Stress Level. Interpretation: As Age increases, Stress Level tends to decrease moderately. In other words, younger individuals may tend to experience higher stress levels compared to older individuals, based on this correlation.

Sleep Duration and Stress Level (-0.811023):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a strong negative correlation between Sleep Duration and Stress Level. Interpretation: As Sleep Duration increases, Stress Level tends to decrease significantly. This suggests that individuals who sleep longer may experience lower stress levels.

Quality of Sleep and Stress Level (-0.898752):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a very strong negative correlation between Quality of Sleep and Stress Level. Interpretation: As the Quality of Sleep improves, Stress Level tends to decrease considerably. This suggests that individuals who have higher-quality sleep tend to experience lower stress levels.

Physical Activity Level and Stress Level (-0.034134):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a very weak negative correlation between Physical Activity Level and Stress Level. Interpretation: There is almost no relationship between Physical Activity Level and Stress Level based on this correlation. The correlation is close to zero, suggesting that Physical Activity Level does not have a significant impact on Stress Level in this dataset.

Heart Rate and Stress Level (0.670026):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a moderate positive correlation between Heart Rate and Stress Level. Interpretation: As Heart Rate increases, Stress Level tends to increase moderately. This suggests that individuals with higher heart rates may tend to experience higher stress levels.

Daily Steps and Stress Level (0.186829):¶

This correlation coefficient indicates a weak positive correlation between Daily Steps and Stress Level. Interpretation: There is a slight tendency for Stress Level to increase slightly as Daily Steps increase. However, the correlation is relatively weak, suggesting that the relationship between Daily Steps and Stress Level may not be very strong.
